\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator considered the original application\'2C the first evaluator\'E2\'80\'99s report\'2C the CHE recommendation and the representation made and came to the conclusion that many of the major concerns raised have not been addressed. The evaluator made the observation that the representation is dominated by broad\'2C philosophical positions that often refer to the delivery of the institutions assembly of instructional programmes and not singularly to the Diploma in Event Management.\line \line There are also significant parts of the representation quoted from a prior evaluation of a programme \'E2\'80\'9CCertificate in HIV\'2FAIDS Counselling and Management\'E2\'80\'9D. Consequently\'2C many areas of institutions representation were misaligned\'2C not only from the fact that education in Event Management functions in a different context\'2C but the needs of learners wanting to pursue this career option is different.\line \line In terms of the reasons for not accrediting the programme\'2C the evaluator argued that the development of appropriate learning materials and platform for student engagement with learning appears very tentative and hypothetical. Coupled with the absence of any Event Management expertise available within the organization there can hardly be any assurance of quality in delivery of the Diploma in Event Management. In addition\'2C there is no evidence of the research and\'2F or evidence to support adequate interrogation of the curriculum by prospective employers. This is especially important\'2C given the vocational focus of the qualification pointed out as Event Manager\'2C Event Coordinator and Event Assistant. While offering promises mainstream event management occupations\'2C a major part of the curriculum is apportioned to learning areas in disciplines that are related to the vocations. However\'2C the evaluator raised the concern that the manner in which they are planned to be presented is generic and often remote to event management.  Other than the modules in event management\'2C other modules have a discipline focus with a \'28generic\'29 prescribed text \'28where stated\'29 that lies outside of the event management sub-field. This is of special concern as the qualification and declared occupational stream is in event management. \line \line While the representation claims that the institution strives to meet international standards\'2C it has not undertaken international comparability for the content of this programme and its delivery via distance education. The articulation possibilities of the programme remain doubtful as the institution has not provided any specific information.  The qualification intends to produce entrants to positions of Event Manager\'2C Event Coordinator and Event Assistant in small\'2C medium or large organisations\'2C but given the vocational nature of these occupations\'2C rigorous procedures for student placement\'2C conduct and supervision of experiential learning is imperative. The representation does not present on how experiential learning component will be supervised. Also\'2C there is no indication of a structure to be expected in workplace learning for the programme. No specific\'2C programme related framework to assure the attainment of workplace learning is available. It could thus be concluded that concerns regarding programme design has not been sufficiently resolved. \line \line Against the background of disadvantaged locations of learners the institution makes a case for distance education solving the lack of access to effective tuition and training \'28albeit in the context of interventions for HIV\'2FAids\'29. However\'2C the human resource needs pertinent to the events industry has not been presented by the institution to justify the proposed curriculum. \line \line The evaluator argued that this justification must necessarily be to the development\'2C execution and delivery of the actual qualification. The quality of distance education received by learners is significantly determined by firstly\'2C explicit communication of the curriculum between learner and the institution and secondly\'2C by the quality of resources developed.  The institution proposes that it will be performing evaluation and development of learning materials\'2C including prescribed texts and technology-based training materials. It is unclear whether the platforms of latter will be interactive computer software\'2C radio\'2C telephone\'2C audio cassettes\'2C satellite television\'2C the internet\'2C or combinations thereof.   However\'2C only a guideline for study guide and film development is provided.  No sample\'2Finitial materials are presented and the appropriateness thereof in terms of distance education cannot be assessed. \line \line In terms of staffing\'2C the evaluator is of the view that the institution does not demonstrate any in-house\'2C academic expertise in the sub-field of the application. \line \line According to the evaluator\'2C the institution claims that it\'E2\'80\'99s supporting resources \'28PC\'E2\'80\'99s for Internet research\'29 and access arrangements are adequate. It also points out that in addition to ICT availability at tuition centres\'2C servers\'2C printers\'2C workstations and peripherals are also available at head office for the use of distance education students. However\'2C indication of primary users\'2C sharing arrangements or volume of users is provided. Additionally\'2C no protocol for access by students of the Diploma in Event Management is available. The evaluator also felt that while the institution claims that its library holdings and access arrangements are adequate for the programme\'2C no list of its collections for the Diploma in Event Management is provided for the assessment of suitability. Only one text in Event Management is available in the full listing contained in the application.\line \line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the decision not to accredit the programme should be upheld. \line \line \cell \pard 

